{{BLP sources|date=January 2013}} {{Use dmy dates|date=July 2012}} {{Infobox person | name = Cecilie Thomsen | image = | caption = | birth_name = <!--if different--> | birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1974|10|29}} | birth_place = [[Bogø]], Denmark | years_active = | occupation = Actress, model | spouse = }}
'''Cecilie Thomsen''' (born 29 October 1974) is a [[Denmark|Danish]] actress and model.
==Early life and education== {{expand section|date=September 2015}} Thomsen was born on the island [[Bogø]] in [[Denmark]].
==Career== Internationally, Cecilie Thomsen is best known for playing the minor [[Bond girl]] role of Professor Inga Bergstrøm opposite [[Pierce Brosnan]] in the 1997 [[James Bond]] feature film ''[[Tomorrow Never Dies]]''.<ref>{{cite web| url= http://www.mi6.co.uk/sections/girls/thomsen.php3 | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20080517182843/http://www.mi6.co.uk/sections/girls/thomsen.php3| archivedate= 17 May 2008| title= Cecilie Thomsen (Professor Inga Bergstrom)| website=MI6.co.uk | accessdate= 26 September 2015| deadurl= yes}}</ref>
She played in duo with [[Henning Moritzen]] in the Danish segment of short film collection ''[[Visions of Europe (movie)|Visions of Europe]]''. The segment is called "Europe doesn't exist" and it was directed by [[Christoffer Boe]].
She starred in the [[Bryan Adams]]' 1995 music video, "[[Have You Ever Really Loved a Woman?]]" directed by [[Anton Corbijn]].<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.nme.com/awards/video/id/hq2KgzKETBw/search/ever | title=Bryan Adams - Have You Ever Really Loved A Woman? video | publisher=''[[NME]]'' | accessdate=2009-09-18 }}</ref>
==Personal life== Thomsen is a Buddhist.
